@model ForkToFit.Models.UserProfile
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Home Page";
}

<div class="text-center">
    <h1 class="display-4">Welcome To Fork To Fit!</h1>
    <h2 class="dislay-4">Your Health Is An Investment, Not An Expense.</h2>
    <div class="text-center container mt-5">


        <form asp-action="DisplayBmrForm">
            <div>
                <h3>Current Bmr</h3>
                @Model.BmrInfo calories <br />
                <button class="btn btn-primary" type="submit">Calculate Bmr</button>
            </div>
        </form>

        <br />
        <p>
            Create a meal plan first then add foods that you would like to include in your diet. In the food selections there will be a list of proteins, carbs and fats to choose from. You can make yourself a breakfast, lunch or dinner meal time but include a single carb, fat and protein source for each meal! If you want to loose weight in a gradual state, then be in a caloric deficit of 100-300 calories, but if you want to go on a faster
            pace, then I suggest being in a 400-500 caloric deficit. On the other hand, being on a 100-300 caloric surplus will gradually help you put
            on weight, but if you want to bulk up faster then I suggest being on 400-500 caloric surplus. My last tip is to cook your food with a zero calorie
            spray, low sodium, low sugar condiments and spices!
        </p>
    </div>
    <br />
    <p>
        Did you know that all foods are divided up
        into a combination of these 3 macronutrients and that's how the calorie
        content is made up of. Protein and carbs are four calories per gram, and fat is nine calories per gram.
        It's all about calories in versus calories out. Through your diet you need to be burning more calories
        than what you are consuming to lose weight. On the contrary, if your goal is to get bigger then you would need
        to eat more calories than what you are burning!
    </p>
</div>
